---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";

const goals = [
  {
    name: "Testability",
    blurb: "Behaviour can be pinned down and verified in isolation.",
  },
  {
    name: "Maintainability",
    blurb: "Change stays cheap as the code and the team grow.",
  },
  {
    name: "Comprehensibility",
    blurb: "Minimal cognitive load — a reader can hold the piece in their head.",
  },
  {
    name: "Decoupling",
    blurb: "Parts depend on as little of each other as possible.",
  },
];
---

<Base title="About" description="What fe-patterns is, and the Goals every pattern serves.">
  <h1>About</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    fe-patterns is a catalog of frontend <strong>Patterns</strong> — reusable
    solutions to recurring problems — together with the Libraries that implement
    them, the Skills that apply them, and the Blog posts that explore them.
  </p>
  <p>
    A Pattern is more than a definition: it ships a Skill that applies, assesses,
    and refactors code toward it, and Guards that keep that code conformant over
    time. The aim is one north star — <strong>help humans and AI agents produce
    high-quality code, fast.</strong>
  </p>

  <h2 id="goals">Goals</h2>
  <p>
    Every Pattern earns its place by advancing at least one Goal — a quality of
    good code that justifies it. The Goals are a flat set:
  </p>
  <ul class="entry-list">
    {
      goals.map((g) => (
        <li>
          <span style="font-weight:600">{g.name}</span>
          <div class="meta">{g.blurb}</div>
        </li>
      ))
    }
  </ul>
</Base>
